solutions.content:
We are given a set of 100 words, from which one was selected to be the secret. 
Each word was generated randomly.
Within 10 guesses we have to find the secret word.
The general idea was implemented many times in the discussion section but how to pick the right guesses is plain wrong.

Let's cover the overall steps:
1. Pick a word (not randomly! We will discuss this in a moment)
2. Run it using the MASTER black box and get back the number of matches with the secret word
3. If it's 6 - return (we found it!)
4. Else - eliminate all the words that don't have the exact same amount of matches with the word from step 1 

These four steps, as I mentioned, can be seen at any post but they usually get steps 1 and 4 wrong.
Let's start with step 4: Why do we need EXACTLY the same amount of matches between the word from step 1 and the master and the word from step 1 with the words we try to eliminate?
It's because if we have too few matches, the tested word can't possibly be the secret word as it's missing crucial letters.
E.g: secret word: "abcde". word from step1: "aaccf" (2 matches). word from step4: "abkde" (1 match with "aaccf").
Note something interesting: "abkde" has more matches with the secret word than the word from step1, it's almost a perfect match, but because it matches only 1 letter from the word from step1 (and not two) we know for a fact that it can't be the secret word.

Ok, but what about words that have more than the needed matches?
E.g: secret word: "abcde". word from step1: "aaccf" (2 matches). word from step4: "aacde" (3 matches with "aaccf").
Since the word from step1 has 2 matches, we know it has (word.length - matches == 3) mismatches.
Any additional match between the word from step1 and step4 means a mismatch for the word in step4

It's crucial to get our heads around this as the wrong logic in step4 can render our solution not good enough

Let's get to the meat of it: How do we choose the right word in step1?
Let me tell you from the get-go - you might pass a few submissions to leetcode by choosing a random word, but eventually, it will fail every now and then. Also, picking a random word without explaining the idea behind it won't fair well for you in an interview.

So, what's the right heuristic? We want to pick the word that has the most matches with all of the other words in the wordlist.
Why is that?
Simple combinatorics will tell us that the chance of any two words in our wordlist to have any match on both letter and index is ~20% (1/26 ^ 6). Which is bad! Think about it, every two words you pick are most likely to not share a single match.
Picking a random word each time means you are 80% likely to return 0 matches from the master which is very bad for our algorithm as we can't rule out any of the other words.

How can we find the word with the most matches you ask? 
We are going to build a frequency map where at each one of the 6 indexes we check what is the most frequent letter and then choose words with the highest "score" (meaning, it has as many matches as possible with the other words in the wordlist)

Armed with these understandings, implementing the code is easy. Good luck (and feel free to ask questions in the comments)

```
var findSecretWord = function(wordlist, master) {
    let MAX_TRIES = 10;

    let badWords = new Set();

    let freq = generateLettersFreq(wordlist);

    for(let i = 0; i < MAX_TRIES; i++) {        
        let word = getNextWord(wordlist, badWords, freq);

        let matches = master.guess(word);
        if(matches == 6) return;

        reduceGuessSpace(word, matches, wordlist, badWords);
        badWords.add(word);
    }

};

let generateLettersFreq = (wordlist) => {
    let freq = new Array(6).fill().map(() => new Array(26).fill(0));
    for(let w of wordlist) {
        for(let i = 0; i < w.length; i++) {
            freq[i][w.codePointAt(i) - 97]++;
        }
    }

    return freq;
}

let getNextWord = (wordlist, badWords, freq) => {
    let bestWord = "";
    let bestScore = -Infinity;

    for(let w of wordlist) {
        let wordScore = 0;
        for(let i = 0; i < w.length; i++) {
            wordScore += freq[i][w.codePointAt(i) - 97];
        }

        if(wordScore > bestScore && !badWords.has(w)) {
            bestWord = w;
            bestScore = wordScore;
        }
    }

    return bestWord;

}

let reduceGuessSpace = (word, mathces, wordlist, badWords) => {
    for(let w of wordlist) {
        let countMatches = 0;
        for(let i = 0; i < w.length; i++)
            if(word[i] == w[i]) countMatches++;

        if(countMatches != mathces) badWords.add(w);
    }
}
```

