The explaination given in Solution is too terse to understand and it took me a while to figure what it's doing. Now that I have figured it (I think) I'd like to share my understanding.

There are 2 parts to this problem. Understanding 1st part is straight forward and I won't spend a lot of time on it. 2nd part is where the magic is.

To begin with, forget Minimax, let's start from scratch.

#### deifnitions
I am going to use the word similarity a lot and here is how I define it (this shouldn't come as surprise):
```
int similarity(String s1, String s2) {
	int res = 0;
	for(int k=0; k<words[i].length(); ++k) if(s1.charAt(k) == s2.charAt(k)) ++res;
	return res;
}
```

Let S be the set of words given to us.
Let T be the target word.

#### Part 1

Let's say you guessed word G. Let x = similarity(G, T).
Obvious way to know what next word to choose is to is to find all words in S which have similarity of x with respect to word G.
Keep iterating and you'll find the right word.

Side note, clear way to make this take less number to attempts is to keep track of all the guesses you did with their similarity with T. So now you have a map/dict which looks like:
```
{
	G1 -> x1,
	G2 -> x2
	...
}
```
Now your next guess should be at exact those similarities from previous guess. So if your next guess was Gn then:
x1 = similarity(G1, Gn)
x2 = similarity(G2, Gn)
etc.
But this is not good enough.

#### Part 2
This is the most intersting part of problem. 

Let G0 be the 1st guess you made and let x = similarity(G0, T).
All words which are at x similarity from T will lie on a circle at distance x from T.
Let all such words be {G0, G1, G2 and G3}, lets calll this set P1 and the visualisation will look as follows:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/user4453/image_1583552193.png)

Key observation here is T is equi-distant (or equi-similarty) from all words in P1.

For every guess you make you want to come closer to T. So if you find every word in S which are as equi-distant (or equi-similarty) from P1 you'll keep getting closer to T.

To visualise, let's say you found that a word G4 in S is exactly equi-similarty from all words in P1, then G4 will be T. This is the curx of it all. As in code below, we are minimising the max-similarty of next candidate in lines:
```
int thisMaxVotes = votes[0];
for (int j = 0; j < 7; ++j) thisMaxVotes = Math.max(thisMaxVotes, votes[j]);

if(minVotes > thisMaxVotes) {
	minVotes = thisMaxVotes;
	res = i;
}
```

Now let's say the next best word G4 which was as equi-similarty from all words in P1 as possible but was not exactly at same similarty. It'd appear like so:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/user4453/image_1583553099.png)

As an excercise, argue what'd happen if G4 lies outside the circle.

Here is the java code
