Assume c0, c1, c2 are all 1D vector of size 2 and they are in the same straight line:
Then the following statement must be true: 
(c1[1]-c0[1])/(c1[0]-c0[0]) == (c2[1]-c0[1])/(c2[0]-c0[0])
However, it might face the overflow caused by the case where denominator is 0.

Here we can uuse cross product theory to aovid the division-by-zero: 
a*d == b * c
same as:
a/b == c/d


So a bette way is: check:
(c1[1]-c0[1]) * (c2[0]-c0[0]) = (c2[1]-c0[1]) * (c1[0]-c0[0])


Solution 1: Use cross product to check collinearity.
```
class Solution {
public: // Time/Space: O(N); O(1)
    bool checkStraightLine(vector<vector<int>>& coordinates) {
        int deltaX = coordinates[1][0] - coordinates[0][0];
        int deltaY = coordinates[1][1] - coordinates[0][1];
        for(int i = 2; i < coordinates.size(); i++)
            if( deltaX * (coordinates[i][1] - coordinates[0][1]) !=  deltaY * (coordinates[i][0] - coordinates[0][0]))
                return false;
        return true;
    }
};
```


Solution 2: Use naive  slope-intercept form:   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope
```
class Solution {
public: // Time/Space: O(N); O(1)
    bool checkStraightLine(vector<vector<int>>& coordinates) {
        auto& basePoint = coordinates[0];
        bool onlyCheckDelta0 = false;        
        float oldSlope;
        for(int i = 1; i < coordinates.size(); i++){
            int delta0 = coordinates[i][0] - basePoint[0];            
            if(delta0 == 0) onlyCheckDelta0=true;
            if(onlyCheckDelta0 && delta0!=0) return false;
            if(delta0 == 0) continue;

            int delta1 = coordinates[i][1] - basePoint[1];            
            float newSlope = (float)delta1/delta0;
            if(i==1) oldSlope = newSlope;
            else if(newSlope != oldSlope) return false;
        }        
        return true;            
    }
};
```

