solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition behind the code is to use dynamic programming to find the minimum number of elements to remove from the input list nums in order to obtain a mountain sequence. So we use the concept of Longest Increasing Subsequence.

Pre-requiasite: First solve Longest Increasing Subsequence for better undersatnding.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

Initialize two arrays, dp1 and dp2, with zeros. These arrays will store the lengths of the longest increasing and decreasing subsequences, respectively, ending at each index.

Use dynamic programming to calculate the length of the longest increasing subsequence (LIS) for each index i in the input list nums. This is done using a nested loop. For each pair of indices (i, j) where 0 <= j < i, if nums[i] is greater than nums[j], we can extend the increasing subsequence ending at index j by including the element at index i. Update inc[i] to be the maximum length of increasing subsequence ending at index i.

Similarly, use dynamic programming to calculate the length of the longest decreasing subsequence for each index i in nums. This is done using another nested loop, but this time we start from the second-to-last index (n-2) and iterate in reverse order.

Iterate through all indices i and find the maximum length of the mountain sequence that can be formed by including index i. This can be calculated as inc[i] + dec[i] - 1.

Finally, the minimum number of elements to remove to obtain a mountain sequence is equal to n - max_length - 1, where n is the length of nums and max_length is the maximum mountain sequence length obtained in the previous step.

Return the minimum number of removals required to obtain a mountain sequence.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
We are using two nested loops that are run twice, so O(n*n).

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
We are using two rows of size n, so O(n)+O(n)~O(n).

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumMountainRemovals(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n=nums.size();
        vector<int>dp1(n,0);

        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            for(int prev=0;prev<i;prev++){
                if(nums[prev]<nums[i] && dp1[i]<dp1[prev]+1){
                    dp1[i]=(dp1[prev]+1);
                }
            }
        }
        vector<int>dp2(n,0);
        for(int i=n-2;i>=0;i--){
            for(int prev=n-1;prev>=i;prev--){
                if(nums[prev]<nums[i] && dp2[i]<dp2[prev]+1){
                    dp2[i]=(dp2[prev]+1);
                }
            }
        }
        int mx=0;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(dp1[i]>0 && dp2[i]>0){
                mx=max(mx,dp1[i]+dp2[i]);
            }

        }
        return n-mx-1;
    }
};
```

