solutions.content:
The whole idea is reducing this problem to finding, for any **VALID** position of the **PEAK**, 
its **maximum INCREASING subarray's length from its left and maximum DECREASING subarray's length from its right**. 

**Maximizing** the length from the left and right means that we re essentially **minimizing** the removals. 

Consider the following example
```
A   = [ 4 , 3 , 2 , 1 , 1 , 2 , 3 , 1 ]
lisL= [ 1 , 1 , 1 , 1 , 1 , 2 , 3 , 1 ]
lisR= [ 4 , 3 , 2 , 1 , 1 , 2 , 2 , 1 ]

Now consider the 6-th element, 
its lisL=3, which basically means the subarray [1,2,3]
its lisR=2, which basically means the subarray [3,1]
if we merge  these two subarrays we get our mountain => [1,2,3,1], of length 4 
so I removed 4 elements to create that, which happens to be the result
```
```
var minimumMountainRemovals = function(A) {
    let n=A.length,
        lisL=[...Array(n)].map(d=>1),
        ldsR=[...Array(n)].map(d=>1)

    // longest Increasing subsequence that ends at i 
    for(let i=0;i<n;i++)
        for (let j = 0; j < i; j++) 
            if(A[i]>A[j])
                lisL[i]=Math.max(lisL[i],lisL[j]+1)
    // longest Decreasing subsequence that starts at i
    for(let i=n-1;i>=0;i--)
        for (let j = n-1; j >i; j--) 
            if(A[i]>A[j])
                ldsR[i]=Math.max(ldsR[i],ldsR[j]+1)

    let result=Infinity
    for (let i = 1; i < n-1; i++) {
        let mountainLength=lisL[i]+ldsR[i]-1
        if(lisL[i]>1&&ldsR[i]>1)
            result=Math.min(result,n-mountainLength)
    }
    return result
};

```

